types.name: MBID
types.description: The `MBID` scalar represents MusicBrainz identifiers, which are 36-character UUIDs.

types.name: Area
types.description: A country, region, city or the like.

types.name: Entity
types.description: An entity in the MusicBrainz schema.

types.name: String
types.description: The `String` scalar type represents textual data, represented as UTF-8 character sequences. The String type is most often used by GraphQL to represent free-form human-readable text.

types.name: Int
types.description: The `Int` scalar type represents non-fractional signed whole numeric values. Int can represent values between -(2^31) and 2^31 - 1.

types.name: Artist
types.description: An artist is generally a musician, a group of musicians, or another music professional (composer, engineer, illustrator, producer, etc.)

types.name: Boolean
types.description: The `Boolean` scalar type represents `true` or `false`.

types.name: LifeSpan
types.description: Begin and end date of an entity that may have a finite lifetime.

types.name: Date
types.description: Year, month (optional), and day (optional) in YYYY-MM-DD format.

types.name: Recording
types.description: Represents a unique mix or edit. Has title, artist credit, duration, list of PUIDs and ISRCs.

types.name: ArtistCredit
types.description: Artist, variation of artist name and piece of text to join the artist name to the next.

enumValues.name: ALBUM
enumValues.description: An album, perhaps better defined as a “Long Play” (LP) release, generally consists of previously unreleased material (unless this type is combined with secondary types which change that, such as “Compilation”). This includes album re-issues, with or without bonus tracks.

enumValues.name: SINGLE
enumValues.description: A single typically has one main song and possibly a handful of additional tracks or remixes of the main track. A single is usually named after its main song.

enumValues.name: EP
enumValues.description: An EP is a so-called “Extended Play” release and often contains the letters EP in the title. Generally an EP will be shorter than a full length release (an LP or “Long Play”) and the tracks are usually exclusive to the EP, in other words the tracks don’t come from a previously issued release. EP is fairly difficult to define; usually it should only be assumed that a release is an EP if the artist defines it as such.

enumValues.name: OTHER
enumValues.description: Any release that does not fit any of the other categories.

enumValues.name: BROADCAST
enumValues.description: An episodic release that was originally broadcast via radio, television, or the Internet, including podcasts.

enumValues.name: COMPILATION
enumValues.description: A compilation is a collection of previously released tracks by one or more artists.

enumValues.name: SOUNDTRACK
enumValues.description: A soundtrack is the musical score to a movie, TV series, stage show, computer game etc.

enumValues.name: SPOKENWORD
enumValues.description: A non-music spoken word release.

enumValues.name: INTERVIEW
enumValues.description: An interview release contains an interview, generally with an artist.

enumValues.name: AUDIOBOOK
enumValues.description: An audiobook is a book read by a narrator without music.

enumValues.name: LIVE
enumValues.description: A release that was recorded live.

enumValues.name: REMIX
enumValues.description: A release that was (re)mixed from previously released material.

enumValues.name: DJMIX
enumValues.description: A DJ-mix is a sequence of several recordings played one after the other, each one modified so that they blend together into a continuous flow of music. A DJ mix release requires that the recordings be modified in some manner, and the DJ who does this modification is usually (although not always) credited in a fairly prominent way.

enumValues.name: MIXTAPE
enumValues.description: Promotional in nature (but not necessarily free), mixtapes and street albums are often released by artists to promote new artists, or upcoming studio albums by prominent artists. They are also sometimes used to keep fans’ attention between studio releases and are most common in rap & hip hop genres. They are often not sanctioned by the artist’s label, may lack proper sample or song clearances and vary widely in production and recording quality. While mixtapes are generally DJ-mixed, they are distinct from commercial DJ mixes (which are usually deemed compilations) and are defined by having a significant proportion of new material, including original production or original vocals over top of other artists’ instrumentals. They are distinct from demos in that they are designed for release directly to the public and fans; not to labels.

enumValues.name: DEMO
enumValues.description: A release that was recorded for limited circulation or reference use rather than for general public release.

enumValues.name: NAT
enumValues.description: A non-album track (special case).

enumValues.name: OFFICIAL
enumValues.description: Any release officially sanctioned by the artist and/or their record company. (Most releases will fit into this category.)

enumValues.name: PROMOTION
enumValues.description: A giveaway release or a release intended to promote an upcoming official release. (e.g. prerelease albums or releases included with a magazine)

enumValues.name: BOOTLEG
enumValues.description: An unofficial/underground release that was not sanctioned by the artist and/or the record company.

enumValues.name: PSEUDORELEASE
enumValues.description: A pseudo-release is a duplicate release for translation/transliteration purposes.

types.name: Release
types.description: Real-world release object you can buy in your music store. It has release date and country, list of catalog number and label pairs, packaging type and release status.

types.name: ReleaseEvent
types.description: Date on which a release was released in a country/region with a particular label, catalog number, barcode, and what release format was used.

types.name: Label
types.description: Labels represent mostly (but not only) imprints.

types.name: IPI
types.description: An IPI (interested party information) code is an identifying number assigned by the CISAC database for musical rights management.

types.name: ReleaseGroup
types.description: Represents an abstract "album" (or "single", or "EP") entity. Technically it’s a group of releases, with a specified type.

types.name: Work
types.description: A distinct intellectual or artistic creation, which can be expressed in the form of one or more audio recordings

types.name: Event
types.description: An organized event which people can attend, usually live performances like concerts and festivals.

types.name: Time
types.description: A time of day, in 24-hour hh:mm notation.

types.name: Place
types.description: A venue, studio or other place where music is performed, recorded, engineered, etc.

types.name: Coordinates
types.description: Geographic coordinates with latitude and longitude.

types.name: Degrees
types.description: Decimal degrees, used for latitude and longitude.

types.name: Instrument
types.description: Instruments are devices created or adapted to make musical sounds.

types.name: URL
types.description: A URL pointing to a resource external to MusicBrainz, i.e. an official homepage, a site where music can be acquired, an entry in another database, etc.

types.name: URLString
types.description: Description

types.name: BrowseQuery
types.description: Browse requests are a direct lookup of all the entities directly linked to another entity.

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name and description, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields` and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FIELD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

enumValues.name: FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field definition.

enumValues.name: ARGUMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an argument definition.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an interface definition.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a union definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum definition.

enumValues.name: ENUM_VALUE
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an enum value definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object type definition.

enumValues.name: INPUT_FIELD_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an input object field definition.

directives.name: include
directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted in [Markdown](https://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/).
